00:00:00,180 --> 00:00:02,460
OK so what is a compromise.

2
00:00:02,460 --> 00:00:07,980
Well you may already know but basically a compromise is when two people who disagree about something

3
00:00:08,400 --> 00:00:15,120
find a space in the middle where one side gives up something and the other side gives up something so

4
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:20,470
that they can agree so that they can come to some sort of agreement.

5
00:00:20,490 --> 00:00:27,630
So the parent who wants their son to study a lot after school is over here the parent who wants their

6
00:00:27,630 --> 00:00:31,410
son to have a lot of free time after school is over here.

7
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:34,400
Well they need to meet in the middle.

8
00:00:34,410 --> 00:00:37,320
It's not going to be only this or only this.

9
00:00:37,350 --> 00:00:43,200
They need to find somewhere in the middle in this spectrum where they agree so that they can actually

10
00:00:43,230 --> 00:00:44,190
get somewhere.

11
00:00:44,220 --> 00:00:44,760
Right.

12
00:00:44,790 --> 00:00:47,610
So they have to find common ground.

13
00:00:47,700 --> 00:00:53,480
This space in the middle between the two extremes of the spectrum.

14
00:00:53,530 --> 00:00:54,770
This is the spectrum.

15
00:00:54,810 --> 00:00:57,260
This area is common ground.

16
00:00:57,270 --> 00:01:04,860
Maybe if our son takes four classes a week for extra classes a week then you'll still have time to hang

17
00:01:04,860 --> 00:01:05,870
out with friends.

18
00:01:05,890 --> 00:01:12,570
OK I could agree to three or four classes a week as long as he can do things he enjoys more creative

19
00:01:12,570 --> 00:01:14,530
things three times a week.

20
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:15,180
Yes OK.

21
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:16,290
That sounds fair.

22
00:01:16,290 --> 00:01:17,770
So they're in here.

23
00:01:17,850 --> 00:01:19,730
Not on the extremes.

24
00:01:19,800 --> 00:01:22,910
They have found common ground.

25
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:24,080
They've met in the middle.

26
00:01:24,090 --> 00:01:24,810
They have.

27
00:01:24,810 --> 00:01:26,980
And this can be a noun or a verb.

28
00:01:26,980 --> 00:01:29,040
It can be a noun or a verb.

29
00:01:29,070 --> 00:01:34,080
They have made they have made a compromise.

30
00:01:34,080 --> 00:01:39,420
They have they have compromised and that's a verb they have made a compromise.

31
00:01:39,420 --> 00:01:41,560
They have compromised.

32
00:01:41,790 --> 00:01:44,220
OK so that's the meaning of compromise.

33
00:01:44,220 --> 00:01:48,760
Now we can look at a couple of expressions when we're ready to compromise.

34
00:01:48,780 --> 00:01:49,090
OK.

35
00:01:49,110 --> 00:01:50,600
So let's look at a few of those.

36
00:01:50,670 --> 00:01:56,370
Now let's take that situation with the two parents who want to compromise.

37
00:01:56,400 --> 00:01:59,930
They have two different views on an issue and they want to compromise.

38
00:01:59,940 --> 00:02:03,450
Well one parent might say I'll tell you what I'll tell you what.

39
00:02:03,450 --> 00:02:06,240
So this is a way to suggest the compromise.

40
00:02:06,240 --> 00:02:07,970
The thing that you're willing to give up.

41
00:02:07,980 --> 00:02:15,150
Tell you what if he can take three classes a week and also play with his friends a few times a week

42
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:17,150
then I think we have a deal.

43
00:02:17,160 --> 00:02:18,110
I think we can agree.

44
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:23,650
Let's talk about a seller for example a seller wants to sell something a buyer wants to buy something.

45
00:02:23,670 --> 00:02:26,250
Seller is giving a very high price.

46
00:02:26,310 --> 00:02:29,250
Buyer doesn't want to pay a high price.

47
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:32,020
They want to pay a low price obviously.

48
00:02:32,180 --> 00:02:32,690
OK.

49
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:36,270
